<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / Smaller companies lead recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHARLES BATCHELOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SMALL manufacturing companies are leading the economy out of recession with
the first improvement in output for three years, the Confederation of
British Industry's Smaller Firms' Trends Survey published today shows.
On balance, manufacturers reporting an increase in output in the four months
to April outnumbered those reporting a decline by 4 percentage points. This
increase was lower than had been expected in January but contrasted with the
manufacturing sector as a whole, which recorded output broadly unchanged,
the CBI said.
Business optimism also rose by a balance of 33 percentage points, the
largest margin for six years. Export orders were the main area of
improvement for both small and large companies.
The survey, the first such by the CBI since the March Budget, covered 800
companies with fewer than 200 employees.
Further increases in output over the next four months are expected by 21 per
cent of companies on balance. A net balance of 25 per cent of small
companies expect orders to increase in the next quarter.
Small companies broadly expect to maintain their spending on plant and
machinery over the next 12 months but a balance of 16 per cent intend to
make further cuts in investments in buildings.
In general, small companies are more optimistic about investment than larger
ones. Small company spending on training and innovation is expected to
increase.
The rate of job-shedding has slowed markedly and is much lower than among
manufacturing companies as a whole. Small companies expecting to take on
staff over the next four months outnumber those expecting to cut jobs by 3
percentage points.
In export markets more small companies were able to raise prices than cut
them for the first time since April 1991.
Domestic prices, however, continued to be cut, although at a much slower
rate. Both export and domestic prices are expected to increase over the next
four months.
Mr Richard Brucciani, chairman of the CBI's smaller firms council, said:
'This is good news for the smaller sector and for the creation of wealth in
our economy as a whole.'
Britain has missed out as an innovator in the manufacture of specialist
equipment to protect the environment, says a report published by a House of
Lords committee today.
Smaller Firms' Economic Report. CBI, Centre Point, 103 New Oxford Street,
London WC1A 1DU. Pounds 5 to members, Pounds 10 non-members.
</TEXT>
