<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / Women hindered in work training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MANAGERS BELIEVE that the biggest barriers to women's training and
development are family commitments, the prejudices of male managers and
child care problems, an Industrial Society survey shows.
The survey, of nearly 400 member companies of the Industrial Society, looked
at general training issues and focused on the training and development of
women employees and secretarial and administrative staff.
On training generally, managers were slightly more pessimistic about the
level of their company spending on training than in a previous society
survey six months ago.
There was also a rise in the proportion of managers who were dissatisfied
with their company's training budgets.
The Industrial Society said one possible explanation for the latter finding
was that after a period of static or minimal growth in training budgets
managers were looking for an increased commitment to training in their
organisation, and they were dissatisfied with the position that they were
in.
On women's training and development the survey found that:
Assertiveness ranked top of managers' priorities for women-only training.
Managers rate the Equal Opportunities Commission as the most important
influence on policies for women's development and training.
Opportunity 2000, a private-sector-led initiative to promote women's
employment, was rated the least influential of the several bodies cited.
Creche provision is very rare during company training courses and 30 per
cent of managers said offers of training had been refused be-cause of family
commitments. About one in 10 managers said they had received complaints from
trainees about discriminatory language in their organisation's training
courses.
Complaints about sexual harassment were very rare.
The findings on secretarial staff suggested they were taking on a growing
number of managerial tasks and spending less time on more traditional
secretarial jobs.
Training Trends. The Industrial Society, 48 Bryanston Square, London W1
H7LN. Pounds 20 or by subscription.
</TEXT>
