<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / Pressure on Patten grows over tests
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OPPOSITION to the government's national curriculum tests hardened at the
weekend.
The National Association of Head Teachers is advising its members today to
ask governors not to provide the Department for Education with test results
necessary for school performance league tables.
Two teachers' unions, the National Association of Schoolmasters/Union of
Women Teachers and the Association of Teachers and Lecturers have voted to
boycott the tests, which are due to take place in June. The National Union
of Teachers seems certain to follow them next week.
Mr David Hart, general secretary of the NAHT, said: 'There seems to be
little point in sending the results through to local education authorities
or to the examining groups or to the Department for Education if they are
going to be used by the government to produce league tables which clearly
are going to be something of a nonsense this year.'
He said that the advice applied only to this year's tests because of the
'peculiar circumstances' of the boycott.
The department deplored the move, saying it was the statutory duty of
governors to assist in producing league tables.
The position of Mr John Patten, the education secretary, could also be made
more difficult by the resignation, expected today, of Lord Skidelsky from
the Schools Examination and Assessment Council. Lord Skidelsky was an early
enthusiast for the national curriculum reforms.
All six teachers' unions have agreed on a submission to Sir Ron Dearing, who
is chairing Mr Patten's review of the national curriculum. They will ask him
to examine the curriculum in its totality, and broaden the remit given to
him by Mr Patten.
The NUT also released a survey of its members on the tests in technology for
14-year-olds. It found that 84 per cent said the tests interfered with
teachers' professional discretion and choices.
Letters, Page 16
</TEXT>
