<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / Eurotunnel to settle bill with shares
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALICE RAWSTHORN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EUROTUNNEL, the troubled Channel tunnel operator, plans to pay part of its
fee to Bechtel, the US construction group, by issuing shares rather than
with cash.
The transaction, which will involve Eurotunnel issuing 2m new shares, comes
at a time of intense speculation about the group's finances because of
costly delays in the tunnel's construction schedule. The anticipated cost of
the project has escalated from Pounds 4.8bn in 1987 to the present estimate
of Pounds 8.4bn.
Eurotunnel, which said last month that it might need to raise up to Pounds
850m in additional cash by the end of 1995 because of the delays, plans to
seek shareholders' agreement for the Bechtel issue at a meeting on June 10.
It will also ask for permission to raise its nominal capital by up to
FFr1.92bn (Pounds 230m) to issue new shares and by FFr565m to issue
warrants.
Bechtel has since 1986 acted as an external consultant to Eurotunnel and has
seconded executives to work for the group. Eurotunnel said that it was
allowed to pay part of Bechtel's bill in shares under the terms of their
agreement.
