<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / Baker Act provoking controversy on national testing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GREATEST power held by county councils has been eroded since their last
elections in 1989 by Mr Kenneth Baker's Education Reform Act, John Authers
writes.
The Baker act, which became law in 1988, is provoking controversy on the
issue of testing for the national curriculum, which it introduced. But it
also introduced the right for schools to opt out of local education
authority control and become 'grant maintained'.
Opted-out schools are funded directly by the Department for Education, and
so many of the powers previously held by local education authorities devolve
to Mr John Patten, the education secretary.
The 1988 act also introduced local management of schools. This aimed to
devolve power away from county halls by creating delegated budgets which
were paid to schools and then put under their control.
Both moves indirectly attacked county councils, which are responsible for
local education authorities outside the metropolitan areas. As the number of
schools opting out has increased, the work remaining for county councils has
decreased.
This has led county councils to fear that there is a link between
grant-maintained schools and the review of the structure of local
government, which is considering replacing two-tier authorities - involving
both counties and districts - with unitary authorities.
Education is the counties' biggest responsibility, and widespread opting out
would make it much easier to do away with county councils altogether.
Not surprisingly, education is proving one of the most important issues in
the campaign for the county council elections.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
