<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / Peru wants to renegotiate debt
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SALLY BOWEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LIMA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PERU'S economic team, led by Mr Jorge Camet, finance minister, is in Paris
today to renegotiate the country's Dollars 8bn (Pounds 5.1bn) debt with its
Paris Club group of creditor countries.
The Peruvian proposal seeks to reduce 1993-95 debt servicing from about
Dollars 1bn (equivalent to one-third of annual export earnings) to between
Dollars 300m and Dollars 350m a year. 'It's a pragmatic proposal aimed at
reducing servicing in line with Peru's ability to pay,' said Mr Eduardo
Valdivia, Peru's chief debt adviser.
Talks with the 17 creditor governments are likely to be tough. But since the
IMF has already approved the current three-year economic programme, Peru is
expected to get most if not all the conditions it seeks.
Ultimately, however, the only realistic solution to Peru's debt burden
appears to be wide-scale forgiveness. Peru proposes to tackle that question
with Paris in three years' time.
</TEXT>
