<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / IG Metall begins strike: Talks today raise hopes of a
settlement in wage dispute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BERLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
IG METALL, Germany's powerful engineering union, is braced today to step up
its strike action in eastern Germany, which began with stoppages at
factories and steel plants in two states yesterday.
But in a hopeful sign last night employers and union officials in the state
of Saxony agreed to hold negotiations this morning to try to resolve the
dispute.
They agreed to this after a four-hour preliminary meeting that also involved
Mr Kurt Biedenkopf, the state's premier.
The strike, the first officially held in eastern Germany since 1933, is over
union demands that employers reinstate a cancelled contract aimed at
equalising wages in eastern and western Germany by next year.
The stoppage yesterday affected five steel plants in Berlin-Brandenburg and
19 metal and engineering sectors in Saxony, as well as the state's four
steel plants. In all, more than 14,000 workers came out in support of IG
Metall, but with less enthusiasm than expected by the union which is
dominated by westerners in eastern Germany.
Mr Franz Steinkuhler, president of IG Metall, told workers in Dresden: 'We
didn't want to strike. We were forced into it by the employers. But we will
strike as long as is necessary and we will win.'
Before Mr Biedenkopf's latest mediation attempt, Mr Steinkuhler warned that
the five eastern German states would be engulfed in an indefinite strike
unless the employers returned to the negotiating table and gave the metal
and engineering sectors a 26 per cent pay increase this year, and the steel
sector a 21 per cent rise.
These claims were part of the original wage contract, signed between IG
Metall and the employers and eastern German managers in March 1991. But the
collapse of the east European and Soviet markets, combined with recession in
western Germany, forced employers to cancel the contract. They have since
recommended pay increases of about 9 per cent.
Both Gesamtmetall, the metal and engineering employers' association, and
Arbeitgeberverband Stahl, the steel employers' association, yesterday said
they would not reinstate the contract. 'We simply cannot afford it,' steel
employers said, adding that much of the sector was already heavily
subsidised and saddled with large debts.
IG Metall claims east Germany should not be turned into a low-wage economy,
even if that makes the region competitive in the long term. Its strategy now
is to increase the number of plants affected by strikes. More than 50
enterprises have been selected in the metal and engineering sectors in
Mecklenburg-West Pomerania and Saxony and steel plants in the five states.
</TEXT>
