<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / Boeing redesigns 747 part
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BOEING, the US aircraft manufacturer, is close to completing the redesign of
a vital component for 747 jumbo jets. A new type of fuse pin used to secure
an aircraft's engine to the wing is likely to be available by late summer.
The redesign follows two airliner crashes in which Boeing 747s are believed
to have lost engines - in October 1992 when an El Al aircraft came down on
Amsterdam and the 1991 crash of a China Airlines 747 in Taiwan.
According to Boeing, investigations into the cause of the first crash showed
that fuse pins may have broken. Inspections have revealed that water
droplets, trapped in the tube-shaped fuse pins, could lead to microscopic
corrosion, which might develop into cracks. The new fuse pin designed by
Boeing is made of stainless steel, which is not susceptible to corrosion.
However, the company said that before the pins could be installed in
aircraft they had to undergo extensive testing and be certified by the US
Federal Aviation Administration. National regulatory agencies will determine
whether a retrofit is mandatory or voluntary. There are more than 900 Boeing
747s in operation.
</TEXT>
