<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / Peace plan may be rejected, warn Bosnian Serbs: Karadzic
expects hard struggle in assembly
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURA SILBER and ROBERT MAUTHNER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
BOSNIAN SERB hardliners yesterday warned that it was far from certain their
self-styled parliament would ratify a Bosnian peace agreement, signed under
great pressure by their leader, Mr Radovan Karadzic, in Athens on Sunday.
The fate of the plan, brokered by Mr Cyrus Vance and Lord Owen, the United
Nations and European Community mediators, now depends on the outcome of a
meeting of the assembly in the Bosnian Serbs' headquarters at Pale, near
Sarajevo, tomorrow.
Both Lord Owen and President Slobodan Milosevic of Serbia, who played key
roles during the hastily convened summit of the Bosnian warring factions in
persuading Mr Karadzic to sign the agreement, have expressed confidence that
the Bosnian Serb assembly would finally endorse it. Mr Milosevic has even
indicated that he would go to Pale to address the assembly.
But Mr Karadzic, who has announced that he will resign if the parliament
rejects the peace plan for a third time, said yesterday he expected a hard
struggle to persuade the parliament to back it.
Under the plan, Bosnia would be divided into 10 semi-autonomous provinces,
largely on ethnic lines, and the Bosnian Serbs would have to give up more
than one-third of the territory they now occupy.
Even more discouraging were the remarks at the weekend of Mr Momcilo
Krajisnik, president of the Bosnian Serb assembly, who said Mr Karadzic's
signature did not in any way mean actual acceptance of the agreement.
'I believe it must be reworked and cannot be accepted in its present form,'
he said.
Meanwhile, Nato's offer to take on the peace-keeping task on behalf of the
UN, which is already overstretched by its commitments around the world,
received a boost yesterday when the White House announced it was prepared to
contribute ground troops to such an operation.
Nato military experts have estimated that implementing the Vance-Owen peace
plan will require at least an extra 60,000 troops, of which the US would be
likely to contribute at least a third.
Sir Nicholas Bonsor, Tory chairman of the House of Commons select committee
on defence, said Britain could possibly provide some 10,000 peace-keeping
troops.
At the same time, the US has made it clear it wants the international
community to keep up the pressure on Serbia and the Bosnian Serbs -
including the preparation of military options - in case the Bosnian Serbs do
not honour the peace agreement.
A statement to this effect was issued after five hours of talks in Britain
on Sunday between Mr Warren Christopher, the US secretary of state, Mr John
Major, prime minister, Mr Douglas Hurd, foreign secretary, and Mr Malcolm
Rifkind, defence secretary.
The statement said the US and UK would continue to develop 'a common
position with our partners and allies on stronger measures to be taken if
the Serbs fail to implement the peace settlement. Several options are under
consideration, including military steps'.
However, no reference was made to well-publicised British reservations about
the desirability of military action.
Mr Christopher yesterday met the foreign ministers of Spain and Greece on
the second day of a mission aimed at building a consensus among western
allies on the need to take military measures if the Bosnian Serbs do not
implement the peace plan. He later flew to Paris and was due to visit Nato
headquarters in Brussels.
In the US, NBC television yesterday reported that US special forces troops
were already in Bosnia, gathering intelligence and selecting potential
targets for air attacks.
West would take strain of Bosnia deal, Page 2
Editorial Comment, Page 17
</TEXT>
