<HEADLINE>
FT  04 MAY 93 / BAe and Matra set to merge missile units
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL BETTS and ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH Aerospace is on the verge of merging its Dynamics missiles
subsidiary with the guided weapons business of the French Matra-Hachette
conglomerate, creating one of Europe's largest guided weapons companies.
The two companies are expected to announce this week agreement to form a
joint company combining their respective guided weapons operations. The new
company's annual turnover will be in excess of Pounds 1bn.
According to today's issue of Flight International magazine, the British and
French governments are 'aware of the situation' and are likely to give their
blessing.
The merger is a significant step in the consolidation and rationalisation of
Europe's defence and aerospace industry, accelerated by the reduction in
government defence spending since the collapse of the eastern bloc.
BAe, one of Britain's largest manufacturing companies, had wanted to form a
partnership with other European defence groups for its missiles operation as
part of its recovery and restructuring strategy.
Two years ago BAe sought to merge its lossmaking guided weapons business
with that of the French-based Thomson-CSF group, but the deal collapsed.
Thomson-CSF has since linked up with Short Brothers of Belfast to develop
short-range ground-to-air missiles.
BAe was in talks with the private Matra group last year for a possible sale
of its space activities to the French company, but the two failed to agree
on a price. However, they maintained close contact and have been negotiating
a merger of their missiles businesses for some months.
With 5,000 employees, BAe's Dynamics division is the larger employer, but
the two missiles businesses have about the same turnover. Matra's missile
sales totalled around FFr5bn (Pounds 600m) last year while BAe's Dynamics
subsidiary had annual sales of around Pounds 500m.
Matra has long wanted to forge a European partnership for its defence
activities in preference to taking part in a restructuring of the French
domestic missiles industry with the state-controlled Aerospatiale and
Thomson-CSF.
The BAe/Matra move coincides with an intensification of missiles
collaboration talks between Aerospatiale and Thomson-CSF, as well as between
Aerospatiale and Deutsche Aerospace.
It is also in line with a wider BAe strategy of strengthening its aerospace
activities through overseas partnerships. It recently merged its regional
jet activities with Taiwan Aerospace, and is engaged in talks with Casa of
Spain and other manufacturers about rationalising its turbo propeller
commuter aircraft business. BAe declined to comment on reports of the
merger.
</TEXT>
