<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 93 / IMF announces global effort to boost growth: Early
completion of the Gatt Uruguay trade round is placed top of the agenda
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN and PETER MARSH
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE membership of the International Monetary Fund last night agreed to join
forces in a 'global co-operative effort' to boost world economic growth and
held out the prospect of lower interest rates in Europe, report Peter Norman
and Peter Marsh in Washington.
After a meeting of the Fund's policy making interim committee, member states
from the industrialised, developing and former communist countries issued a
unanimous declaration spelling out the efforts each group would make to
achieve sustained global expansion.
Most of the individual measures have already been announced by national
governments and their effectiveness will depend on their successful
implementation. But the statement will provide policy makers with a
checklist to ensure that their countries are living up to promises made to
boost growth.
The finance ministers and central bank governors comprising the interim
committee said they would monitor developments carefully to ensure the
hoped-for recovery will be consolidated. They said they supported
strengthening the IMF's surveillance of member policies so that problems in
the world economy such as crises on foreign exchange markets could be
identified and tackled in a timely manner.
Early completion of the Uruguay Round of trade liberalisation talks was put
at the top of the list of measures to boost growth. The declaration said
that there was an 'immediate and urgent need' for a successful conclusion to
the round. 'Persistent failure to complete the round would not be a
standstill, but could reverse the trend of trade liberalisation which has
been an important contributor to growth'.
The statement allocated responsibilities to each group of countries.
Developing nations were urged to carry forward their economic reform
programmes. The statement said that the transformation of the former
communist countries to market based economies was a key element of the
co-operative growth effort. They were promised increased financial and
technical help while the finance ministers who drew up the statement urged
improved access for their goods to foreign markets.
The industrialised countries were allocated the 'central responsibility' for
strengthening growth prospects. The statement recalled the efforts already
being made by Japan to increase domestic demand and the US to reduce its
budget deficit. In Europe, it said conditions which should allow for a
further progressive reduction in interest rates are expected to continue to
improve in the period ahead.
The statement emphasised the importance of medium term strategies for
deficit reduction in nations such as the US with large structural budget
deficits. These would have a 'major favourable impact of interest rates,
private investment and job creation.'
Earlier, Mr Lloyd Bentsen, the US Treasury secretary, warned the US recovery
would be moderate. Other industrial countries would have to boost demand to
achieve a stronger world economy while the US cut its budget and trade
deficits.
</TEXT>
<XX>
