<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 93 / World Stock Markets (America): Blue chips lower after late
program selling
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Wall Street
AFTER HOLDING firm in positive territory for most of the day, a late round
of program selling left blue chip stocks slightly lower at the close, writes
Patrick Harverson in New York.
At the close the Dow Jones Industrial Average was down 2.43 at 3,427.55,
well below its peak of 3,446.19. Other indices fared better. The more
broadly based Standard&amp;Poor's 500 ended 1.30 higher at 440.19, the Amex
composite finished up 2.21 at 420.96, and the Nasdaq composite rose 2.97 to
661.42. Volume on the NYSE was 240m shares, and rises outpaced declines by
1,205 to 669.
Thursday's late rally, when prices recovered from early losses to end
broadly higher, set the tone for a confident start to trading. Within
minutes of the opening, the Dow was up almost 15 points as buying followed
through from the end of the previous session.
Dealers said that buying was a mixture of computer program trading, and some
end-of-month acquisitions by big institutions. Sentiment was also buoyed by
news that flows of investors' cash into stock mutual funds had reached
record levels in March and the first quarter, and by an early decline in
bond yields. Bond yields, however, later reversed direction, and combined
with a rush of late sell programs to leave Dow stocks with modest declines
at the end of trading. Economic news was mostly ignored because of the
conflicting nature of the reports. Personal income rose 0.6 per cent in
March, but personal spending fell 0.2 per cent and factory orders dropped
1.5 per cent, also last month.
Interest in cyclical stocks revived, in spite of recent poor economic news.
Allied Signal rose Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 65 1/4 , International Paper
added Dollars  3/8 at Dollars 65 3/4 , and Caterpillar rose Dollars  1/2 to
Dollars 69 1/4 .
Bethlehem Steel rose Dollars 1 to Dollars 19 5/8 in volume of almost 1m
shares after the company said it would raise prices on steel plate products
on July 4 by Dollars 10 to Dollars 20 a ton. Aetna jumped Dollars 3 1/8 to
Dollars 52 7/8 after the life and casualty insurer announced first quarter
net income of Dollars 166.3m, well up on the Dollars 118.7m earned in the
same period a year ago.
Eastman Kodak rose Dollars  3/8 to Dollars 48 3/4 on reports that the
company plans to sell a major asset to improve shareholder value. Genentech
climbed Dollars 4 3/4 to Dollars 37 1/2 on the news that the company's
blood-clot dissolving agent, Activase, had better results in preventing
heart attack deaths than a rival product. On the Nasdaq market Lin
Broadcasting rose Dollars 1 3/4 to Dollars 89 after a ratings upgrade from
Prudential Securities.
Canada
TORONTO STOCKS extended their winning steak to four sessions, closing higher
in moderately active trading. Based on preliminary data, the 300 composite
index was up 34.35 points, or 0.91 per cent, to 3,789.41, with advances
leading declines 460 to 270.
PWA Corp. reported increased losses in the first quarter but said it has
resumed making payments to its creditors as of today. PWA rose CDollars 0.03
to CDollars 0.53.
</TEXT>
