<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 93 / UK Company News: BPCC considers market flotation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY and MAGGIE URRY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BPCC, Britain's largest commercial printing company, is likely to go for a
Stock Exchange flotation either late this year or early next.
The company, formally owned by the late Mr Robert Maxwell but sold when he
pulled out of printing, has started work on the 'beauty parade' to choose
financial advisers for the flotation.
'I'm not saying we are floating in October but we have started the process,'
Mr John Holloran, BPCC's chief executive, said yesterday.
The company, which prints nine of the top ten magazines in the UK from the
Radio Times to Woman's Own, left the Maxwell empire in January 1989 in a
Pounds 235m management buy-out.
The inspiration for the possible flotation has come from the company's new
chairman, Mr Brian Garraway, who retired recently as deputy chairman of BAT.
Timing would depend on market conditions as the printing industry starts to
pull out of recession.
Mr Holloran said that if the company decided to go ahead with a float 'the
earliest would be towards the end of this year and it could roll into next
year.'
Last year BPCC had a turnover of Pounds 289m with an operating profit of
Pounds 19.5m. After interest charges of Pounds 26m the company made a
pre-tax loss of Pounds 5m.
Since the buy-out the BPCC chief executive says Pounds 94m has been invested
in re-equipping printing plants and as a result a number of contracts lost
to continental European printers have been regained.
</TEXT>
