<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 93 / Sell gold, IMF urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR Norman Lamont, the UK chancellor, yesterday suggested that the
International Monetary Fund should sell some of its gold to help finance IMF
assistance for the poorest developing nations.
In his speech to the IMF's policy-making interim committee, Mr Lamont said
he 'would not rule out some modest sales of IMF gold to fund at least part'
of a successor to the IMF's extended structural adjustment facility (ESAF)
which provides funds at token interest rates to poor developing nations
carrying out economic reforms.
The ESAF totals SDRs6bn (about Pounds 5.5bn) and is due to expire next
November. The industrialised countries that provide the fund have so far
been unable to agree on how to finance a successor, largely because of the
budgetary constraints on most of them.
British officials said preliminary discussions had been held in the IMF
board of directors about whether to sell some of the Fund's gold. Although
Mr Lamont put forward the idea in his speech yesterday, he is not committed
to it, they said. 'He wants to see the issue explored,' one added.
One suggestion put forward by the British Treasury was that the IMF should
sell between 10m and 15m ounces of gold over 10 years to provide about half
the funds needed for new ESAF funds. Because ESAF costs only build up
gradually, the gold sales would not need to begin until 1996.
Britain is keen for the international community to agree on a successor to
ESAF because it believes it is a good policy instrument for spreading sound
economic policies in developing countries.
The UK also has close ties with many of the countries that use ESAF funds,
particularly in Africa.
The IMF sold gold in 1976 to set up a trust fund that was a precursor of
ESAF and also provided finance for developing countries.
However, the present IMF management has been hostile to further gold sales.
Mr Michel Camdessus, the IMF managing director, has described the IMF's gold
as the 'jewel of the family'.
The IMF's gold holdings amount to 103.44m ounces and are valued
conservatively at 35 special drawing rights an ounce in the IMF's accounts.
A substantial obstacle to IMF sales of gold is the condition that they must
be approved by 85 per cent of the total voting power of the Fund's members.
</TEXT>
