<HEADLINE>
FT  01 MAY 93 / US acts against Japan on trade: Clinton takes tougher stance
to force opening of foreign markets
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GEORGE GRAHAM and PETER NORMAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US yesterday launched a salvo of tough trade actions against Japan,
Brazil, India, Thailand and several other trading partners.
The move provoked an immediate hostile response from Japan and heralded a
new era of trade friction with several other countries.
The measures are likely to add to foreign governments' perplexity over the
direction of US trade policy. Just the night before, Mr Clinton told finance
ministers of the Group of Seven industrialised countries, meeting in
Washington, that the US was ready to take 'exceptional actions' to bring
about agreement in the stalled Uruguay Round of trade liberalisation talks.
Mr Clinton's remarks were echoed yesterday by Mr Lloyd Bentsen, the US
treasury secretary, who told the IMF the US wanted the Tokyo summit in July
to seek a G7 agreement on market access issues holding up a Uruguay Round
agreement. The round should be concluded by mid-December, he said.
Yesterday's tough US measures target the Japanese government's procurement
practices in construction and supercomputers, while taking aim at abuses of
intellectual property rights in the other countries.
Mr Mickey Kantor, US trade representative, invoking US laws against foreign
government discrimination on procurement, said President Clinton's
administration was 'taking a different tack' from the Bush administration in
seeking more rigorous enforcement of US trade laws and bilateral trade
agreements.
Mr Kantor argued that these enforcement actions were intended not just to
open foreign markets for US goods and services, but to restore credibility
to the idea of open trading.
He said tough action could help to develop public support for free trade in
the US, where protectionist sentiments are mounting against the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade and the North American Free Trade Agreement.
The strongest action announced yesterday was against Japanese practices in
awarding construction contracts. Citing 'persistent and significant
discrimination against US firms', Mr Kantor threatened sanctions within 60
days if the issue was not resolved.
Angry Japanese officials warned that they might retaliate against US
contractors and insisted that negotiations would not begin with the US under
the threat of time limits or sanctions.
Japanese officials interpreted the move by the US trade representative's
office as a sign of the Clinton administration's tougher stance on the
bilateral deficit. Japan also sees the US action as an opportunity to show
it will resist bilateral trade agreements.
The US earlier this month used the same law to invoke sanctions against the
European Community in the telecommunications and heavy electrical equipment
sectors. Sanctions are due to be imposed in the telecommunications area.
Procurement practices were also listed as concerns in Australia and China.
Mr Kantor complained of Japanese discrimination against US supercomputer
suppliers and ordered a review of Japanese actions under a 1990
supercomputer agreement.
A senior Japanese foreign ministry official said the timing of the US action
could damage multilateral negotiations under Gatt. 'We are ready to discuss
the construction market but we will never do so under threat of sanctions,'
he said.
At the same time, the US listed Brazil, India and Thailand as 'priority
foreign countries' because of their denial of adequate intellectual property
protection. Other countries also targeted for action on the intellectual
property issue were Hungary, Taiwan, Korea, Argentina, Egypt, Poland,
Turkey, Australia, Saudi Arabia and the EC.
The US move came as G7 finance ministers agreed this week that a further
opening of the international trading system was indispensable for maximising
world growth.
IMF effort on growth, Page 3
Japan backed on trade, Page 3
E Europe trade links, Page 24
</TEXT>
